{
  "name": "Bhai Jagtar Singh & Harinder Singh Fakkar (Patiala)",
  "url": "https://kirtansewa.net/index.php/bhai-jagtar-singh-harinder-singh-fakkar-patiala/",
  "image_url": "https://cdn.kirtansewa.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/22011621/Bhai-Jagtar-Singh-Fakkar-1.jpg",
  "body": [
    "Bhai Jagtar Singh Fakkar is the son of Bhai Sarmukh Singh Fakkar, one half of the famous duo of Bhai Gurmukh Singh & Sarmukh Singh Fakkar who served as Raagis in Nankana Sahib prior to the division of Punjab. They belong to the Rababi heritage of music and one of their ancestors before them became Amritdhari Sikhs. Following the partition of Punjab, they settled in Patiala along with many other Rababi families that became practicing Sikhs. Bhai Jagtar Singh Fakkar had 5 sons, of which the oldest was Bhai Harinder Singh Fakkar who accompanied him for all his tours around the globe. His other sons include Bhai Dalip Singh Fakkar, Bhai Harcharan Singh Fakkar, Bhai Inderjit Singh Fakkar and Bhai Himmat Singh Fakkar. All of the recordings below are of Bhai Jagtar Singh Ji, accompanied on the side by Bhai Harinder Singh Fakkar and Bhai Dalip Singh Fakkar on tabla. They traveled to Singapore, Malaysia, USA and Canada. Bhai Jagtar Singh Ji passed away during his tour to Los Angeles, USA. Ironically, over 30 years later Bhai Harinder Singh Fakkar also passed away in Los Angeles while he was on tour. Bhai Harinder Singh Fakkar trained under both Patiala and Sham Chaurasi Gharana. His initial training was with Ustad Baqar Hussain Khan of Patiala Gharana and subsequently he learned from Ustad Salamat Ali Khan of Sham Chaurasi Gharana for 5 years. He trained his younger brothers as well and after their father’s death, the jatha of Bhai Harinder Singh and Bhai Harcharan Singh Fakkar were a force to be reckoned with. They also performed in classical Mehfils under the name Thakur Bandhu. Unfortunately, this ‘jori’ was short lived as Bhai Harcharan Singh Fakkar passed away at the very young age of 34. I have uploaded recordings of Bhai Harcharan Singh Fakkar on a separate page so please have a look at that too. If anyone has more recordings of the ‘Fakkar’ family to share, please contact us."
